orical material from a variety of sources, Stephen shows how activists have appropriated symbols of the revolution to build the contemporary political movement. Her wide-ranging narrative touches on the history of land tenure, racism, gender issues in the Zapatista movement, local political culture, the Zapatista uprising of the 1990s and its aftermath, and more. A significant addition to our knowledge of social change in contemporary Mexico, Zapata Lives! also offers readers a model for engaged, activist anthropology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aIndians of MexicoxGovernment relationsxMexicoxChiapas. 0aIndians of MexicoxSocial conditions. 0aIndians of MexicozMexicozChiapasxGovernment relations. 0aIndiens d'AmériquexConditions socialesxMexique. 0aIndiens d'AmériquexRelations avec l'ÉtatxMexiquexChiapas. 0aMouvements sociauxxHistoirex20e sièclexMexique. 0aSocial movementsxHistoryx20th centuryxMexico. 0aSocial movementszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520927643423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520927643.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles